<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many blocks do I need for a retaining wall?", answer: "Calculate the number of rows by dividing the wall height (in inches) by the block height. Calculate blocks per row by dividing the wall length (in inches) by the block length. Multiply rows by blocks per row and add 10% for waste. Standard 6-inch-high by 16-inch-long blocks are the most common size for residential retaining walls." },
  { question: "How much gravel do I need for a retaining wall base?", answer: "The gravel base should be 6 inches deep and 24 inches wide (wider than the blocks). Multiply 0.5 feet (depth) by 2 feet (width) by the wall length in feet, then divide by 27 to convert cubic feet to cubic yards. This compacted gravel base provides drainage and a level foundation for the first course." },
  { question: "How much backfill do I need behind a retaining wall?", answer: "Backfill is typically 12 inches deep behind the wall for its full height. Multiply the wall height by 1 foot (depth) by the wall length, then divide by 27 for cubic yards. Use clean gravel for the bottom two-thirds of backfill and topsoil for the upper third to support plantings." },
  { question: "Do I need a permit for a retaining wall?", answer: "Most jurisdictions require a building permit for retaining walls over 4 feet high (measured from the bottom of the footing to the top of the wall). Walls near property lines, public sidewalks, or supporting surcharges (driveways, structures) may require engineering regardless of height. Always check local building codes." },
  { question: "How high can I build a retaining wall without engineering?", answer: "Most residential retaining walls up to 3-4 feet high can be built without professional engineering, depending on local codes. Walls over 4 feet typically require engineered plans, a building permit, and inspection. Gravity walls (without reinforcement) should generally not exceed 3 feet. Taller walls need geogrid reinforcement, proper drainage, and compacted backfill." }
]) %>

